by foot. I know, who would have thought. I tried to get to the grocery store by taxi for the first two weeks thinking such small distances called for using a taxi service. My friends all ask me why I didn’t know this, but after doing some research and learning, I found that most taxis in Comoros charge a fixed rate per day that depletes after they reach their limit of kilometers. Once a day is over and over again surpassed, the taxi then resets back to ROD 150 on the next day. A taxi for the whole day costs ROD 1100 which equates to USD 12 for 24 hours. Of course, way cheaper than a taxi at ROD 500 per single trip of about 1km, but very expensive to pay ROD 500 for a return trip to the market maybe once a week. Once I priced out a taxi for one day and the market was about 1km away, I had my mind set on completing the walking portion of the journey by foot. There was a clearer view and walking home also gave me a sense of accomplishment. The entire thing takes about 20-25 minutes each way depending what time of day I go. During rush hour the traffic was crazy, but during my weekday evening visits it was mostly just mopeds, taxis, and the occasional night market shopper routing around on foot while checking out the market.
